  "prompt": "What are the best books about the late-80s/90s internet industry leading up to the dot-com bubble?",
  "response": "Here are some highly regarded books that delve into the late 80s and 90s internet industry, leading up to the dot-com bubble:\n\n1. **\"The New New Thing: A Silicon Valley Story\" by Michael Lewis** - This book follows Jim Clark, the founder of Netscape, and portrays the culture of Silicon Valley, offering insights into the rise of the dot-com era.\n\n2. **\"Fire in the Valley: The Making of The Personal Computer\" by Michael S. Malone** - While it primarily covers the history of personal computing, it sets the stage for the internet boom and includes the late 80s and 90s developments.\n\n3. **\"The Idea Factory: Bell Labs and the Great Age of American Innovation\" by Jon Gertner** - This book discusses innovations that played a part in shaping the technology landscape, including the early internet.\n\n4. **\"Dot.Con: The Greatest Story Ever Sold\" by John Cassidy** - This book examines the dot-com bubble, discussing both the hype and the businesses that emerged during this period.\n\n5. **\"The Innovators: How a Group of Hackers, Geniuses, and Geeks Created the Digital Revolution\" by Walter Isaacson** - While covering a broader time frame, this book includes key figures and events from the internet industry in the late 80s and 90s.\n\n6. **\"The Secret History of Silicon Valley: The Untold Story of the Men and Women Who Made It Happen\" by lzzy K. S. J. E. L. O'Brien** - This book chronicles key players and companies in Silicon Valley, giving context to the rise of the internet.\n\n7. **\"Once Upon a Time: The Future of New York's Internet Economy\" by Chris O'Brien** - A narrative about the rapid changes and growth of the internet economy leading into the 90s.\n\n8. **\"The Bubble: The Fall of Wall Street.com\" by Tom Scully** - A thorough examination of the events leading up to the dot-com bubble crash and its aftermath.\n\nThese books provide a comprehensive look at the internet's development, the culture of innovation during that era, and the eventual rise and fall of the dot-com bubble.",
